ng and orbited bodies' b'g\t gravitational constant (defined below)' b'u\t g m (can be measured much more accurately than g or m)' b'k\t -g m a' b'r\t radius of orbit (measured from center of mass of system)' b'v\t orbital velocity' b'p\t orbital period' b'a\t semimajor axis of orbit' b'' b'vc\t sqrt(m g r)' b'vesc sqrt(2 m g r) sqrt(2) vc' b'v^2 u/a' b'p\t pi/(sqrt(u/a^3))' b'k\t v**2 g m r (conservation of energy)' b'' b'the period of an eccentric orbit is the same as the period' b'of a circular orbit with the same semi-major axis.' b'' b'change in velocity required for a plane change of angle phi in a' b'circular orbit:' b'' b'delta v sqrt(gm/r) sin (phi/2)' b'' b'energy to put mass m into a circular orbit (ignores rotational' b'velocity, which reduces the energy a bit).' b'' b'gmm (1/re 1/2rcirc)' b're radius of the earth' b'rcirc radius of the circular orbit.' b'' b'classical rocket equation, where' b'dv\t= change in velocity' b'isp specific impulse of engine' b've\t= exhaust velocity' b'x\t= reaction mass' b'm1\t= rocket mass excluding reaction mass' b'g\t= m s^2' b'' b've\t= isp g' b'dv\t= ve ln((m1 x) m1)' b'= ve ln((final mass) (initial mass))' b'' b'relativistic rocket equation (constant acceleration)' b'' b't (unaccelerated) c/a sinh(a*t/c)' b'd c**2/a (cosh(a*t/c) b'v c tanh(a*t/c)' b'' b'relativistic rocket with exhaust velocity ve and mass ratio mr:' b'' b'at/c ve/c ln(mr), or' b'' b't (unaccelerated) c/a sinh(ve/c ln(mr))' b'd c**2/a (cosh(ve/c ln(mr)) b'v c tanh(ve/c ln(mr))' b'' b'converting from parallax to distance:' b'' b'd (in parsecs) p (in arc seconds)' b'd (in astronomical units) p' b'' b'miscellaneous' b'f=ma force is mass times acceleration' b'w=fd work (energy) is force times distance' b'' b'atmospheric density varies as exp(-mgz/kt) where z is altitude, m is' b'molecular weight in kg of air, g is local acceleration of gravity, t' b"is temperature, k is bolztmann's constant. on earth up to km," b'' b'd d0*exp(-z*1.42e-4)' b'' b'where d is density, d0 is density at 0km, is approximately true, so' b'' b'' b'atmospheric scale height\tdry lapse rate' b'(in km at emission level)\t (k/km)' b'-------------------------\t--------------' b'earth\t 7.5\t\t\t b'mars\t 11\t\t\t b'venus\t 4.9\t\t\t b'titan\t 18\t\t\t b'jupiter\t 19\t\t\t b'saturn\t 37\t\t\t b'uranus\t 24\t\t\t b'neptune\t 21\t\t\t b'triton\t 8\t\t\t b'' b'titius-bode law for approximating planetary distances:' b'' b'r(n) 2^n astronomical units (n -infinity for' b'mercury, for venus, for earth, etc.)' b'' b'this fits fairly well except for neptune.' b'' b'constants' b'' b'6.62618e-34 j-s (7e-34) planck\'s constant "h"' b'1.054589e-34 j-s (1e-34) planck\'s constant pi), "h bar"' b'1.3807e-23 j/k\t(1.4e-23) boltzmann\'s constant "k"' b'5.6697e-8 w/m^2/k (6e-8) stephan-boltzmann constant "sigma"' b'6.673e-11 n m^2/kg^2 (7e-11) newton\'s gravitational constant "g"' b'0.0029 m k\t (3e-3) wien\'s constant "sigma(w)"' b'3.827e26 w\t (4e26) luminosity of sun' b'1370 w m^2\t solar constant (intensity at au)' b'6.96e8 m\t (7e8)\t radius of sun' b'1738 km\t\t (2e3)\t radius of moon' b'299792458 m/s\t (3e8) speed of light in vacuum "c"' b'9.46053e15 m\t (1e16) light year' b'206264.806 au\t (2e5) b'3.2616 light years (3)\t parsec' b'3.0856e16 m\t (3e16) b'' b'' b'black hole radius (also called schwarzschild radius):' b'' b"2gm/c^2, where g is newton's grav constant, m is mass of bh," b'c is speed of light' b'' b'things to add (somebody look them up!)' b'basic rocketry numbers equations' b'aerodynamical stuff' b'energy to put a pound into orbit or accelerate to interstellar' b'velocities.' b'non-circular cases?' b'' b'' b'next: faq astronomical mnemonics' 